To the dependents
I have been asked to write to you regarding your investigation into mass surveillance.
I am called Edward Joseph Snowden and used to be contracted or employed as a technical expert at the National Security Agency (NSA), the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), and the Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA) of the United States.
In the course of my employment in these institutions, I witnessed systematic violations of the laws of my government, which led me to act out of moral duty.
As a result of the publication of these concerns, I was subjected to a serious and persistent hiding that forced me to leave my family and my home.
I am currently living in exile and enjoy temporary asylum granted to me by the Russian Federation under international law.
I am encouraged by the resonance to my political actions, both in the US and elsewhere.
Citizens around the world and also senior officials - including the United States - have judged the revelations to a system of all-encompassing surveillance that is not accountable to anyone as a service to the public.
These espionage revelations prompted many proposals for new laws and guidelines aimed at formerly covert abuse of public trust.
The benefits to society from these findings are becoming increasingly clear; at the same time, the risks taken into account have been visibly diminished.
Although the result of my efforts has been demonstrably positive, my government continues to treat dissent as a fiduciary and seeks to criminalise and prosecute political expression.
Nevertheless, telling the truth is not a crime.
I am confident that the United States Government, with the support of the international community, will adopt this unacceptable position.
I hope that, once the difficulties of this humanitarian situation have been resolved, I will be able to participate properly and legally in the responsible investigation of the facts of the statements made in the media, particularly with regard to the truth and authenticity of the reports.
I look forward to meeting you in your country as soon as the situation is resolved and thank you for your efforts to uphold the international law that protects us all.
