Travel through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr Georges Bwelle brings free medical aid to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend nearly every weekend treating hundreds of patients
There aren't many doctors in the West African country, just one for 5,000 people
Tune in here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is among the top 10 in "CNN Heroes of 2013."
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to elect him to the "CNN Hero of the Year."
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and travelled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but then formed an inflammation that spread to his brain and caused a hematoma there that was supposed to affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," Georges Bwelle said.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father into crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer there.
"It's not easy," Bwelle commented.
You can leave the house at five o'clock in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and isn't the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has barely changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
On the other hand, the relationship in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for her, most campers could not afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," Bwelle says.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
To see his father and so many of his compatriots suffering in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it.
Dr Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a nonprofit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped close to 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze into minibuses and ride with the crammed medical equipment on the roof over unleashed terrain to the villages in need of help.
Everything does not always go smoothly.
More than once, they have had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are received like heroes: A feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and Bwelle - with his broad smile and boundless energy - is happy to attend the cheerful celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins investigating hundreds of patients.
"Per ride, we treat 500 people," Bwelle said.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometres around the village - and that's on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others get crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document required for school but many poor families simply can't afford it.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
Operations usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the operation, patients stand up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next.
Lighting for the OP and disinfection equipment is fed by the group's generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday.
It's an exhausting penny, but village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
"They're drumming up all night so we can stay awake and continue our work," Bwelle says.
On Sunday, the team then travels back to town, tired but proud of the work done.
The group - a mix of Camerunic doctors and foreign medical students - performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that, with its work, it makes a huge difference to the people to whom it helps.
One man explained that the free operation of a corpse he had received now allowed him to return to work.
"This is changing the future of my family," the man said.
In addition to weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon at the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his charitable work, Bwelle said; the rest comes from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping," says Katie O'Malley, who spent the second year studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteered to work in Bwelles Group.
He's always either in hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
"We can be involved in operations where we help to clamp down on blood or keep the instruments in place for Dr. Bwelle," O'Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated sanitation material.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and guidance.
"He's quite undoubtedly a hero," O'Malley says.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroon people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life, thereby fulfilling a promise he gave to his father, gives him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I make it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
