Pope Francis appoints first Cardinals in February
Pope Francis will convene new cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time on February 22, as the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest-ranking clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope, and they are also the ones who elect a pope, so that Francis will appoint the first group of men who will eventually be involved in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 Cardinals.
However, a cardinal who reaches an age of 80 can no longer take part in the pope's election - that falls to a group of 120 "eligible cardinals."
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said there would be a meeting of all the cardinals before the ceremony to appoint the new cardinals, also known as the Consistorium.
"Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene consistency in February in advance so that other meetings requiring the participation of cardinals from around the world can be planned," Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of eligible Cardinals voters was likely to have fallen by February.
He explained that a pope usually harbours as many cardinals as he needs to, so that the number of eligible cardinals back 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he wants.
The consistency next year is significant because it is the first since the election of Francis in March this year, Valero said.
There is currently a certain overhang on the part of Europe and, in particular, Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he said.
Forty per cent of Catholics live in South America, yet they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The Cardinals will also be the first to be appointed since the formation of the Council of Cardinals, founded by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from around the world charged with finding ways to reform the church.
In the past, the pope decided everything alone.
"Now Francis has selected these eight cardinals to help him," Valero said.
He declared it was "well possible" that Francis would ask the Cardinals for advice.
So far, however, we have not been in this situation - it is all very new.
Valero said that typically the bishops would be called to cardinals from large places, but stealing Francis "full of surprises - so we don't know who he is appointing."
