Syria has destroyed its ability to manufacture chemical weapons, according to a monitoring group
Syria had destroyed key facilities for producing chemical weapons and grid gas munitions, the global chemical weapons monitoring group said on Thursday, while severe clashes occurred in the north of the country near one of the sites where suspected toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed since the civil war began soon three years ago.
The announcement by the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came a day before the deadline on
November 1, which the Hague-based organization had set up Damascus to destroy or "inoperable" all facilities for producing chemical weapons, including all machines for mixing chemicals into toxic gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is basically the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all Syria's chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Damascus, however, has yet to begin destroying its existing weapons and stockpiles.
According to assumptions, there are about 1,000 tonnes of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting took place in the city of Safira on Thursday, which experts say is where there is a production facility for chemical weapons as well as storage facilities, according to the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
The activist group, which tracks the number of dead across a network of activists in Syria, said on Thursday that 120.296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, 29,954 of them belonged to President Bashar Assad's army, 18,678 were pro-government fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army figures and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the number of deaths in the conflict to be 100,000 since March 2011.
That number has not been updated so far.
The conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country.
Assad's forces have been fighting in Safira for weeks against the rebels, many of whom have ties to al-Qaeda groups.
The Observatory said there had been losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not provide details.
The fighting underscores the danger that chemical weapons inspectors face, because their mission to liberate Syria from its toxic arsenal is a race against time amid a towering civil war.
According to the OPCW, which is working closely with the United Nations, the team is "now convinced that it has seen all the important production and mixing / filling facilities mentioned by Syria and witnessed their destruction."
That is why 'no further inspection activities are currently planned'.
Earlier in the week, inspectors had said they had completed the first round of checks and visited 21 of 23 of the sites specified by Damascus.
Due to safety concerns, the visit of two facilities would not have been possible, the inspectors said.
On Thursday, OPWC said the two sites had been "abandoned, according to Syrian testimony... and that the chemical weapons program's objects there had been relocated to other named facilities that were inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has put forward a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by OPWC's executive committee next month.
"I pull the hat off the bravery and courage you have all shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organisation," Ahmed Uzumcu, the monitoring organization's director general, explained in a commentary published by OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting a secession from Shia Islam in this civil war against Assad's government and its security forces, which include many members of the Alawites.
Regarding further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said there had been a strong explosion on Wednesday at an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion was not known, he explained.
