At least six authorities worldwide - the European Commission, FINMA, the Swiss competition authority WeKo, the FCA, the US Department of Justice, and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are currently dealing with allegations that bankers are alleged to have agreed to transactions in the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received information requests from authorities, said people familiar with the situation.
Banks are cracking instant messages and emails from several years in search of cases of wrongdoing.
News of these investigations has put traders in turmoil in an area that has been among the most profitable of investment banks "trading units in recent years, but has been under pressure this year because low volatility in currencies limits opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to downplay the affair, saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the vast and highly liquid foreign exchange market, but leading traders believe that this is not necessarily true.
A leading retailer noted that, despite the enormous daily volume of foreign exchange trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between the various trading platforms and the increasing use of its own internal platforms by banks leads to "you being able to influence the market even with very low ticket prices."
The news came out the same day as Credit Suisse announced it had cancelled a retailer of its London Exchange traded funds office this week after causing a loss of just under $6 million at the end of last year.
The bank promptly informed the relevant authorities and is cooperating with them.
"We are sure the retailer acted alone and that the matter is contained," Credit Suisse explained.
