African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white age genosines, research shows.
Physical changes don't mean puberty right now
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced among boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter is already growing breasts and shamhairs at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the Children's Medical Association American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents - normally that's not an indication that puberty is now fast entering," Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious displays of development, such as growing breasts, shaming and artery hair as well as body smell, show up in girls earlier.
Yet there has been only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (occurrence of the first rule bleeding) over the past 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When the development of breasts begins, it still takes at least two to three years to menarche," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early puberty in girls: The essential counselor for dealing with this common problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty is progressing.
It is controversial what is actually the beginning of puberty, but it is "early ripe" for breast enlargement to be accompanied by a growth boost before an age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates - something a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, tests could be shown by an endicronologist so that serious problems such as tumours or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatments for delaying early menstruation and defying another consequence: Premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth impairment and therefore small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for medication or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reticent about medication, but he admits: "Suppressing puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and the feelings of girls, unlike being their age genosines."
The other big problem is understandable: Parents just don't want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They worry because of pregnancy risk or about how they handle the hygienic side," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter got her days off with ten.
Even though there were initial signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home frightened and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media would be the cause.
Young come into puberty similar to girls earlier in the day.
Kaplowitz believes the most compelling premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported conducting a study in 2001 on girls aged six to nine, which established a link between body fat and entry into puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white age genosines.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, an early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys have been growing facial and shamelessness before, the trend towards full-scale earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and shaming hair is common even among babies and toddlers.
