What happens to my e-mail on the way?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
In the design of the Internet service e-mail similar to traditional mail, has the letter secrecy been technically implemented?
In the conception of early Internet services, the emphasis was on making communication possible.
Therefore, in the basic technical protocols, no effort has been made to establish a stable foundation for a radio-safe exchange of letters.
Therefore, a traditional e-mail is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If user "Anna" sends a mail to "Benni," are the computers of the two then directly connected?
Anna's e-mail program or browser will send the mail to her service provider's mail server in the first step.
For example, if she has a GMail account, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the track, the mail can run via a number of other servers on the internet.
Bennie can then call the content at his provider.
Are traditional e-mails read on their way through the network?
Most mails are read several times by software robots on the way.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an appendix.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiver systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is a annoying and unwanted spam mail that is deleted immediately or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have yet another task?
In systems like GMail, the robot also detects the information that Google needs to place context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip, Google may display appropriate links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also read the emails with?
The likelihood of unauthorized people reading a mail is extremely low.
In theory, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the ability to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal options to intercept or take note of emails.
There is also the possibility of illegal postponement.
Is it possible to protect e-mails against co-reading?
With an encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be encrypted effectively against co-reading.
With high technical effort, it is also possible to conceal the metadata of an e-mail communication so that it is not even easy to identify who has communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the e-mail market in Germany?
According to an August 2013 investigation by Convios Consulting, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the mainly privately used mailboxes.
While Yahoo Mail's shares had last fallen, GMail was able to make clear from Google.
