Hearing before Royal Commission: Two YMCA staff accused of sex offences against Jonathan Lord
Two YMCA staff from New South Wales (NSW) had been charged with child sex offences before charges were brought against child care provider Jonathan Lord from Caringbah in 2011, as the Royal Commission into Sexual Abuse of Children learned.
But in the opening statement before the commission, the YMCA had stated that "one in the organisation had never had to deal with an incident of sexual child abuse."
Managing director Phillip Hare was questioned about a case in which a YMCA employee had been charged with offences involving child pornography and another in which a sports instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall had been convicted of abusing children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, one of the commission's assisting lawyers, that he had known of the first case but had not known the second.
He admitted that the YMCA's opening statement to the commission was also inaccurate in claiming "there have been external reviews of the YMCA in which the YMCA has been recognised as being at the forefront of child safety."
Evidence before the commission instead shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit by the Department of Education and Communities (Department of Education) in August of the year.
Hare, who started at the YMCA at 21, admitted that the management had "failed to step down from me" in hiring Lord and did not ensure staff had been aware of their obligations to report breaches of child safety guidelines.
Lord had been convicted earlier this year of sex offences against 12 boys during his two-year tenure for the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare denied, however, that the YMCA had a cultural problem that had prevented staff from reporting Lords breaches in relation to child safety.
Staff said they had observed breaches, including that Lord was alone with children, looked after them privately as babysitters, let them sit on his lap, said to one he loved, and let children play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who asked for child protection training because she was concerned about his behaviour, said the child services chief Jacqui Barnat, who was the superiority Lords at the YMCA Caringbah, was "very intimidating and very unassuming most of the time."
The managing director stated that he would not accept statements from employees that they had not dared to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, their friendship with Lord had affected their judgment, which is why they had not reported him.
Hare said he told the board of YMCA NSW his view was that the lesson the organisation had to draw from the "Jonathan Lord incident" was "not the meltdown" by staff, and the board had agreed to it.
Hare said the decision to urge staff to sign secrecy obligations shortly after the allegations appeared was made by the YMCA's managing director of children's services, Liam Whitley.
He said this was intended to prevent contamination of the evidence, but which had been "over-zealous" and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW had not been a safe organisation for children in the period when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, an expert on sexual child abuse, told the commission.
He explained that there had been "serious problems" in recruiting, reviewing, engaging, training and supervising staff.
The hearing was adjourned until December 20.
Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At about 120 metres in length below Cologne, a sewage channel from the Roman period has been preserved.
Those who visit Cologne will not pass the Cathedral.
About 157 metres up the two towers into the sky, making it the second highest church building in Europe.
But few visitors, who marvel at the two filigree church towers, suggest that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral, too.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne's underworld.
The meeting point for its guided tours is the service centre of Cologne-Tourismus directly at the Cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: "We're catching up in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the Seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, which is why the remains of the old city wall remained just what was not too big.
Most of the users of the car park pass by the remains of the Roman Empire and leave their cars alone.
But if you look more closely, an archaeological site separated by metal grid roofs is discovered in the parking deck D2.
Some five-metre-high ruins of hand-made stones can be seen.
"These are remnants of the Roman city wall that was built in the second half of the first century after Christ," Schulze tells.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets participants take a look at a sinister 15-metre deep shaft at the upper parking level.
This is the fountain of the old Cathedral, which unfortunately is hardly noticed either.
Next stop of the tour is the pretorium, and here the participants descend back down into the deep.
Here we experience the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the precursor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means is a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for" Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium, "which in good German means as much as" City of Roman Law and City of Agrippine, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the Imperial cult. "
And the Pretorium is the former statue palace, the centre of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the front room of the exhibition there is a tunnel access to the Roman sewage channel, which is preserved here at about 120 meters in length.
"You can quietly walk a piece along the so-called Cloaca Maxima, if you like," Schulze encourages guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After picking up the key at the box office, he leads the group to a 16-metre deep, walk-in shaft.
"We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built its bathroom deep into the ground to get to the groundwater, which was essential for ritual washing.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels are readable by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on Town Hall Square for which construction work is due to begin shortly.
However, it will be a few years before completion.
