George Kerevan: European unbundling gives Scots the choice
A new day, a new horror story on independence.
This time we are being warned that an independent Scotland was needed to join the Schengen area as a condition of EU membership.
That provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed-wire border along the Hadrian wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde proposal highlighted the potential economic benefits that would bring more freedom of movement in the rest of Europe, but this did not play a part in the headlines, as expected.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favourable to them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued disregard for Brussels would be only a small concession in return for what you really want from the Scots.
So actually no story.
And one that has come in such a way in the years that it already resembles a fossil: The first time I've heard the "independence means passport controls" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance according to the European pipe?
Why swap the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: The grand post-war plan to unify Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project has officially died.
All over the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Party Alternative for Germany - founded only this year - was able to secure nearly five million votes in the federal election in September, effectively expelling Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis is turning out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, together with the straitjacket into which the national economy is forced by adherence to the single currency, many people believe that the European project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits - only in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has fixed its members at exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters - and German politicians would like to leave it that way.
Without the possibility of devaluing the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage over Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending - boosted by Berlin.
Behind the current budgetary and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the "green" energy directives imposed by Brussels - a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times for gas compared with the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world's wage caps do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is gathering, especially in France, the EU's former cheerleader.
After the war, France's political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and lift Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, which is causing the troubled French economy to struggle.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU National Front has just won a decisive re-election, putting the ruling Socialists in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the popular vote - a timely warning for Britain's Labour Party that it cannot assume a split on the right would automatically mean benefits to the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newly won popularity among white working-class French?
It wants to use next year's EU elections to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community monetary bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections - and this is very possible - then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: In the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of joining the US.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in Atlantic rain.
Where does Scotland stay on all this?
We can decide to be a region of (in final consequence) Klein-England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests - which includes telling Berlin and Brussels what they can get stuck in.
I suspect Scotland could fare very well in a looser European composite, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similar countries is easier in an unfederated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same for Norway and retaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is - remarkably - the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and pre-approved) cuts that Labour finance minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory Lib Dem coalition had to blame.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to be forced into austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in planes (but don't make mobile calls)
Air passengers can now, from departure to landing, use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but don't phone with the cellphone, according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the US.
But passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented hinge on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew's training manuals and the rules on stocking the equipment in accordance with the new rules.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among those airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in a statement.
Currently, passengers will have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors close.
They will not be allowed to restart them until the plane reaches a height of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing flight, passengers must turn it off again and not restart it before the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes were secured against electronic disruptions could allow their passengers to use the devices even at launch, landing and on the rolling field, the FAA explained.
Most new commercial aircraft and other fliers that have been converted to use Wi-Fi at greater heights should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional flight attendants' association, welcomed the changes.
"If the new scheme is safely implemented - and we are working closely with the airline in this regard - both sides will benefit," Glading commented.
To be honest, we are tired of having to feel like passers-by on this issue.
However, internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data below three kilometres remained banned, the authority explained.
Passengers are urged to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends," the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to publicly leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the boarding gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be dusted, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight also remain banned.
The regulatory competence for phone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA suspends possible ban on certain electronic devices at launch and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, security expert on national traffic issues on CBS News, said cellphones would still be considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also disrupt transmitter masts," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate the issue recommended last month that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics like Democratic senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri believe there are no valid safety reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies say that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the device's shutdown.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air passengers in 1966, after reports of disruptions to navigation and communications devices by passenger-led UKW radios that represented the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electric systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA so that electronic interference does not make them anything.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers for a number of years when flight height is reached.
The fliers adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the greater use of electronic devices, according to the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally produce significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only give out minimal radiation when you're fumbling.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Advocates of easing restrictions on device use by passengers include Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees invited a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to identify problems, but could not identify any.
Members of the FAA advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the passenger association National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the disruption caused by the devices was genuine, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only single reports of pilots pretending to disrupt aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended to the FAA that pilots should be allowed to arrange for passengers to switch off the equipment during instrument landing under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes, calling them a sensible adjustment for travellers who would now be extensively equipped with technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
