According to Jonathan Martin, national policy correspondent for the Times, the book painstakingly traces the history of the efforts of senior staff of the campaign and the White House, notably former White House Chief of Staff Bill Daley, to gauge the effect it has on the poll ratings of exchanging former Secretary of State Clinton for vice president.
The potential change was a closely guarded secret within the campaign infrastructure in Chicago and the Oval Office.
Only half a dozen of the president's closest advisers - including Daley, Obama's former campaign manager, Jim Messina, and the former White House senior adviser, David Axelrod, and David Plouffe - knew about the planned change.
"Double Down" claims that Daley has been at the forefront of efforts to exchange bids despite her "close, personal relationship" before finally deciding against such a move, after data showed that Clinton's candidacy "would not significantly improve Obama's chances."
