Despair of an Obama voter
I have elected President Obama twice in the hope that change is possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by the Republican nominee's blockadetachment
The blockade policy does not excuse Obamacare's website problems, the drone strikes
Obama's memoirs about the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what might have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm currently reading a terribly sad book.
It's a book I believed it would enlighten me during the divisive second year of my medical studies and give me hope again.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and depicts Barack Obama's memoirs for the 2008 presidential election.
When I am finished and go to bed with my patients' papers in the evening, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could breathe breath into a speech.
The election became a landslide victory and news speakers held on to highlight the historic significance of this hour.
My classmates cried with joy and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama moved to office in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a nasty awakening, as if taken out of a dream.
It's hard to remember these optimistic times - they seem a vague reminder, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, something has actually changed.
But it's just nothing I could have imagined.
I acknowledge the great and versatile things Obama has achieved, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act on health insurance to military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of forced concealment of homosexuality in the army, and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I agree that partisan blockadetachment has dumped too many aspirations that our nation should be moving forward with: Immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and closing Guantanamo Bay, to name but a few.
But, having defended the Obama administration countless times against colleagues and acquaintances, I ended up with my attempts to explain.
I have reached a point of political despair.
Republican blockade policy cannot explain why interception of foreign heads of state is allowed or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers who disclose state misconduct are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits were circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the results of a report that says the White House's efforts to ruin the media are the "most aggressive... since the Nixon administration."
And, more recently, it can't excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act passed.
I don't know if it's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood, at 18, that government work could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously, the Chamber of Deputies is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape public debate.
But when I look at the examples above, they seem to be largely chosen by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unelaborate alternative, he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from pressure from future elections, would fulfil the hope of which we had been hearing for so long.
But with the drop in approval ratings for Obama at below 45% this week, the return to 2008 through this book has become all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have broken up into air.
This week, I read a section in the book describing how Obama had to mount a heavy loss against Clinton in the Pennsylvania primaries.
In a meeting with election aides after the decision, he told his staff they would have to come back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to regain our spell," he said.
We have to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree more strongly with you.
The views expressed in this comment are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris.
